  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering.  Here are some of the most significant:\n\n*   **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)** (Vienna Convention): This convention was one of the first major international efforts to address money laundering, though it primarily focused on proceeds from drug trafficking. It requires signatory states to criminalize the laundering of money derived from drug-related offenses.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)** (Palermo Convention): This convention expanded the scope of money laundering offenses beyond drug trafficking to include proceeds from a wider range of serious crimes, including organized crime. It also promotes international cooperation in investigation and prosecution of money laundering.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003)** (Merida Convention): This convention requires states to criminalize the laundering of proceeds of corruption, including bribery and embezzlement of public funds.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations:** While not a treaty or convention, the FATF Recommendations are the globally recognized international standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and the financing of proliferation of weapons of mass destruction.  They provide a comprehensive framework of measures that countries should implement to prevent, detect, and punish these activities.  FATF is an inter-governmental body. Although the FATF recommendations are not legally binding, many countries have incorporated these recommendations into their domestic laws and regulations, making them influential in shaping anti-money laundering (AML) frameworks worldwide.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990)** (Strasbourg Convention, CETS No. 141): This convention was specifically focused on money laundering and provided a framework for international cooperation in identifying, tracing, freezing, seizing, and confiscating the proceeds of crime.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime and on the Financing of Terrorism (2005)** (Warsaw Convention, CETS No. 198): This convention updated the Strasbourg Convention and expanded its scope to include the financing of terrorism.\n\nThese international instruments demonstrate a global consensus on the need to combat money laundering and promote international cooperation to achieve this goal. Countries that are party to these conventions are obligated to implement their provisions into their national laws and regulations.",
